[src:dremio/apache-arrow] Arrow can be used with Apache Parquet, Apache Spark, NumPy, PySpark, pandas and other data processing libraries.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] The project includes native software libraries written in C, C++, C#, Go, Java, JavaScript, Julia, MATLAB, Python (PyArrow), R, Ruby, and Rust.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] Arrow allows for zero-copy reads and fast data access and interchange without serialization overhead between these languages and systems.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] Arrow has been used in diverse domains, including analytics, genomics, and cloud computing.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] Apache Parquet and Apache ORC are popular examples of on-disk columnar data formats.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] Arrow is designed as a complement to these formats for processing data in-memory.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] The hardware resource engineering trade-offs for in-memory processing vary from those associated with on-disk storage.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] The Arrow and Parquet projects include libraries that allow for reading and writing data between the two formats.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] Apache Arrow was announced by The Apache Software Foundation on February 17, 2016, with development led by a coalition of developers from other open source data analytics projects.
[src:dremio/apache-arrow] The initial codebase and Java library was seeded by code from Apache Drill.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:dremio/data-lakehouse] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Unlike the traditional extract, transform, load ("ETL") process, the data remains in place, and real-time access is given to the source system for the data.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] This reduces the risk of data errors, of the workload moving data around that may never be used, and it does not attempt to impose a single data model on the data (an example of heterogeneous data is a federated database system).
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] The technology also supports the writing of transaction data updates back to the source systems.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] To resolve differences in source and consumer formats and semantics, various abstraction and transformation techniques are used.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] This concept and software is a subset of data integration and is commonly used within business intelligence, service-oriented architecture data services, cloud computing, enterprise search, and master data management.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] The defining feature of data virtualization is that the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] This aids in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] As a result, data virtualization creates new possibilities for data use.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Building on this, data virtualization's real value, particularly for users, is its declarative approach.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Unlike traditional data integration methods that require specifying every step of integration, this approach can be less error-prone and more efficient.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Traditional methods are tedious, especially when adapting to changing requirements, involving changes at multiple steps.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Data virtualization, in contrast, allows users to simply describe the desired outcome.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] The software then automatically generates the necessary steps to achieve this result.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] If the desired outcome changes, updating the description suffices, and the software adjusts the intermediate steps accordingly.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] This flexibility can accelerate processes by up to five times, underscoring the primary advantage of data virtualization.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Connection problems occur more often in complex systems where one or more crucial sources will occasionally be unavailable.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Smart data buffering, such as keeping the data from the most recent few requests in the virtualization system buffer can help to mitigate this issue.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Moreover, because data virtualization solutions may use large numbers of network connections to read the original data and server virtualised tables to other solutions over the network, system security requires more consideration than it does with traditional data lakes.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] In a conventional data lake system, data can be imported into the lake by following specific procedures in a single environment.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] When using a virtualization system, the environment must separately establish secure connections with each data source, which is typically located in a different environment from the virtualization system itself.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Security of personal data and compliance with regulations can be a major issue when introducing new services or attempting to combine various data sources.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] When data is delivered for analysis, data virtualisation can help to resolve privacy-related problems.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Virtualization makes it possible to combine personal data from different sources without physically copying them to another location while also limiting the view to all other collected variables.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] However, virtualization does not eliminate the requirement to confirm the security and privacy of the analysis results before making them more widely available.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Regardless of the chosen data integration method, all results based on personal level data should be protected with the appropriate privacy requirements.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Some enterprise landscapes are filled with disparate data sources including multiple data warehouses, data marts, and/or data lakes, even though a Data Warehouse, if implemented correctly, should be unique and a single source of truth.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Data virtualization can efficiently bridge data across data warehouses, data marts, and data lakes without having to create a whole new integrated physical data platform.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Existing data infrastructure can continue performing their core functions while the data virtualization layer just leverages the data from those sources.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] This aspect of data virtualization makes it complementary to all existing data sources and increases the availability and usage of enterprise data.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Data virtualization may also be considered as an alternative to ETL and data warehousing but for performance considerations it's not really recommended for a very large data warehouse.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Data virtualization is inherently aimed at producing quick and timely insights from multiple sources without having to embark on a major data project with extensive ETL and data storage.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] However, data virtualization may be extended and adapted to serve data warehousing requirements also.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] This will require an understanding of the data storage and history requirements along with planning and design to incorporate the right type of data virtualization, integration, and storage strategies, and infrastructure/performance optimizations (e.g., streaming, in-memory, hybrid storage).
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Data virtualization software may include functions for development, operation, and/or management.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] A metadata engine collects, stores and analyzes information about data and metadata (data about data) in use within a domain.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Enterprise information integration (EII) (first coined by Metamatrix), now known as Red Hat JBoss Data Virtualization, and federated database systems are terms used by some vendors to describe a core element of data virtualization: the capability to create relational JOINs in a federated VIEW.
[src:dremio/data-virtualization] Another more up-to-date list with user rankings is compiled by Gartner.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] One approach is grid computing, where the processing power of many computers in distributed, diverse administrative domains is opportunistically used whenever a computer is available.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] An example is BOINC, a volunteer-based, opportunistic grid system, whereby the grid provides power only on a best effort basis.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] Another approach is grouping many processors in close proximity to each other, as in a computer cluster.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] In such a centralized system the speed and flexibility of the interconnect becomes very important, and modern supercomputers have used various approaches ranging from enhanced InfiniBand systems to three-dimensional torus interconnects.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] The term also applies to massively parallel processor arrays (MPPAs), a type of integrated circuit with an array of hundreds or thousands of central processing units (CPUs) and random-access memory (RAM) banks.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] These processors pass work to one another through a reconfigurable interconnect of channels.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] By harnessing many processors working in parallel, an MPPA chip can accomplish more demanding tasks than conventional chips.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] MPPAs are based on a software parallel programming model for developing high-performance embedded system applications.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] Goodyear MPP was an early implementation of a massively parallel computer architecture.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] MPP architectures are the second most common supercomputer implementations after clusters, as of November 2013.
[src:dremio/massively-parallel] Data warehouse appliances such as Teradata, Netezza or Microsoft's PDW commonly implement an MPP architecture to handle the processing of very large amounts of data in parallel.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Generally, the query optimizer cannot be accessed directly by users: once queries are submitted to the database server, and parsed by the parser, they are then passed to the query optimizer where optimization occurs.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] However, some database engines allow guiding the query optimizer with hints.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] A query is a request for information from a database.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Since database structures are complex, in most cases, and especially for not-very-simple queries, the needed data for a query can be collected from a database by accessing it in different ways, through different data-structures, and in different orders.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Each different way typically requires different processing time.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Processing times of the same query may have large variance, from a fraction of a second to hours, depending on the chosen method.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The purpose of query optimization, which is an automated process, is to find the way to process a given query in minimum time.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The large possible variance in time justifies performing query optimization, though finding the exact optimal query plan, among all possibilities, is typically very complex, time-consuming by itself, may be too costly, and often practically impossible.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Thus query optimization typically tries to approximate the optimum by comparing several common-sense alternatives to provide in a reasonable time a "good enough" plan which typically does not deviate much from the best possible result.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] There is a trade-off between the amount of time spent figuring out the best query plan and the quality of the choice; the optimizer may not choose the best answer on its own.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Different qualities of database management systems have different ways of balancing these two.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Cost-based query optimizers evaluate the resource footprint of various query plans and use this as the basis for plan selection.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] These assign an estimated "cost" to each possible query plan, and choose the plan with the smallest cost.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Costs are used to estimate the runtime cost of evaluating the query, in terms of the number of I/O operations required, CPU path length, amount of disk buffer space, disk storage service time, and interconnect usage between units of parallelism, and other factors determined from the data dictionary.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The set of query plans examined is formed by examining the possible access paths (e.g., primary index access, secondary index access, full file scan) and various relational table join techniques (e.g., merge join, hash join, product join).
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The search space can become quite large depending on the complexity of the SQL query.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] These consist of logical optimization—which generates a sequence of relational algebra to solve the query—and physical optimization—which is used to determine the means of carrying out each operation.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Most query optimizers represent query plans as a tree of "plan nodes".
[src:dremio/query-optimization] A plan node encapsulates a single operation that is required to execute the query.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The nodes are arranged as a tree, in which intermediate results flow from the bottom of the tree to the top.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Each node has zero or more child nodes—those are nodes whose output is fed as input to the parent node.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] For example, a join node will have two child nodes, which represent the two join operands, whereas a sort node would have a single child node (the input to be sorted).
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The leaves of the tree are nodes which produce results by scanning the disk, for example by performing an index scan or a sequential scan.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The performance of a query plan is determined largely by the order in which the tables are joined.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] For example, when joining 3 tables A, B, C of size 10 rows, 10,000 rows, and 1,000,000 rows, respectively, a query plan that joins B and C first can take several orders-of-magnitude more time to execute than one that joins A and C first.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Most query optimizers determine join order via a dynamic programming algorithm pioneered by IBM's System R database project .
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The optimizer then considers combining each pair of relations for which a join condition exists.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] For each pair, the optimizer will consider the available join algorithms implemented by the DBMS.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] It will preserve the cheapest way to join each pair of relations, in addition to the cheapest way to join each pair of relations that produces its output according to a particular sort order.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Then all three-relation query plans are computed, by joining each two-relation plan produced by the previous phase with the remaining relations in the query.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Sort order can avoid a redundant sort operation later on in processing the query.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Second, a particular sort order can speed up a subsequent join because it clusters the data in a particular way.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] A SQL query to a modern relational DBMS does more than just selections and joins.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] In particular, SQL queries often nest several layers of SPJ blocks (Select-Project-Join), by means of group by, exists, and not exists operators.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] In some cases such nested SQL queries can be flattened into a select-project-join query, but not always.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Query plans for nested SQL queries can also be chosen using the same dynamic programming algorithm as used for join ordering, but this can lead to an enormous escalation in query optimization time.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] So some database management systems use an alternative rule-based approach that uses a query graph model.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] One of the hardest problems in query optimization is to accurately estimate the costs of alternative query plans.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Optimizers cost query plans using a mathematical model of query execution costs that relies heavily on estimates of the cardinality, or number of tuples, flowing through each edge in a query plan.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Cardinality estimation in turn depends on estimates of the selection factor of predicates in the query.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Traditionally, database systems estimate selectivities through fairly detailed statistics on the distribution of values in each column, such as histograms.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] This technique works well for estimation of selectivities of individual predicates.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] However many queries have conjunctions of predicates such as `select count(*) from R where R.make='Honda' and R.model='Accord'`.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Query predicates are often highly correlated (for example, `model='Accord'` implies `make='Honda'`), and it is very hard to estimate the selectivity of the conjunct in general.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Poor cardinality estimates and uncaught correlation are one of the main reasons why query optimizers pick poor query plans.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] This is one reason why a database administrator should regularly update the database statistics, especially after major data loads/unloads.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Classical query optimization assumes that query plans are compared according to one single cost metric, usually execution time, and that the cost of each query plan can be calculated without uncertainty.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Both assumptions are sometimes violated in practice and multiple extensions of classical query optimization have been studied in the research literature that overcome those limitations.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Those extended problem variants differ in how they model the cost of single query plans and in terms of their optimization goal.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Classical query optimization associates each query plan with one scalar cost value.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization assumes that query plan cost depends on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Such parameters can for instance represent the selectivity of query predicates that are not fully specified at optimization time but will be provided at execution time.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Parametric query optimization therefore associates each query plan with a cost function that maps from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a one-dimensional cost space.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is usually to generate all query plans that could be optimal for any of the possible parameter value combinations.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] This yields a set of relevant query plans.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] At run time, the best plan is selected out of that set once the true parameter values become known.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The advantage of parametric query optimization is that optimization (which is in general a very expensive operation) is avoided at run time.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] There are often other cost metrics in addition to execution time that are relevant to compare query plans.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] In a cloud computing scenario for instance, one should compare query plans not only in terms of how much time they take to execute but also in terms of how much money their execution costs.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Or in the context of approximate query optimization, it is possible to execute query plans on randomly selected samples of the input data in order to obtain approximate results with reduced execution overhead.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] In such cases, alternative query plans must be compared in terms of their execution time but also in terms of the precision or reliability of the data they generate.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Multi-objective query optimization models the cost of a query plan as a cost vector where each vector component represents cost according to a different cost metric.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Classical query optimization can be considered as a special case of multi-objective query optimization where the dimension of the cost space (i.e., the number of cost vector components) is one.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Different cost metrics might conflict with each other (e.g., there might be one plan with minimal execution time and a different plan with minimal monetary execution fees in a cloud computing scenario).
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Therefore, the goal of optimization cannot be to find a query plan that minimizes all cost metrics but must be to find a query plan that realizes the best compromise between different cost metrics.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] What the best compromise is depends on user preferences (e.g., some users might prefer a cheaper plan while others prefer a faster plan in a cloud scenario).
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Multi-objective parametric query optimization generalizes parametric and multi-objective query optimization.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Plans are compared according to multiple cost metrics and plan costs may depend on parameters whose values are unknown at optimization time.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The cost of a query plan is therefore modeled as a function from a multi-dimensional parameter space to a multi-dimensional cost space.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] The goal of optimization is to generate the set of query plans that can be optimal for each possible combination of parameter values and user preferences.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] A number of tools display query execution plans to show which operations have the highest processing cost.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Microsoft SMS, ApexSQLPlan, Hana, and Tableau are some examples.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] Fixing these issues found in these plans can shave tens of percent execution time, and in some cases can cut two-dimensional searches to linear ones.
[src:dremio/query-optimization] One of the primary and simplest optimization checklists is to use operations that most RDMS are designed to execute efficiently.
